    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>California <hi rend="underline">San Fran</hi></placeName>
                <date>May 29 1862</date>
            </p>
            <p>Reply to “Wrong doings in <placeName>California</placeName></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Revd. Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">My attention has<lb/> been drawn to the above article in the<lb/>
                gleaner of the <date>23d</date> Inst. copied from<lb/> the Occident of <date>April
                    62</date>—in which it<lb/> states “Two <persName>C<hi rend="underline"
                        >ohamin</hi></persName> applied to<lb/> congregation “Sherith Israel” to be
                mar-<lb/>-ried by <persName>Dr. Henry</persName> to widows, and<lb/> he refused.”
                    <persName>Theophilis</persName> (upon whom<lb/> I suspect I could lay my
                finger)<lb/> does <hi rend="underline">not</hi> tell the Truth. <hi rend="underline"
                    >I</hi> am the<lb/> wife of one of the “<persName>Cohanim</persName>”
                alluded<lb/> to, and beg to state the facts to<lb/> you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I arrived in <placeName>California</placeName> in <date>1850</date>,
                and<lb/> in the spring of <date>1852</date> left with my<lb/> first husband on a
                trading voyage<lb/> to the <placeName>South Pacific Islands</placeName>, and</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">2</p>
            <p>unfortunately lost him at one of the<lb/> Tonga<add>?</add> group in <date>September
                    1852</date>l, I returned<lb/> to this city <date>Dec. 27<hi rend="sup"
                    >th</hi></date> of the same year<lb/> dreadfully distressed in mind—in<lb/> fact
                inconsolable. My Father (god rest<lb/> his dear soul) was here till <date>July
                    1854</date><lb/> during that period he made the ac-<lb/>-quaintance of
                    <persName>Mr. P.</persName> and wished me<lb/> very much to marry him. I
                told<lb/> him no—but so anxious was<lb/> he, that, previous to his departure for<lb/>
                <placeName>New York</placeName> he left word with a friend<lb/> to occasionally urge
                the matter to me.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In <date>1858</date> I was engaged to<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. P.</persName> but called his attention to Chap. 21<lb/> V. 14 of
                Leviticus: he said he would con-<lb/>-sult a <hi rend="underline">Lamdan</hi>, which
                he did, and<lb/> this gentleman said, <hi rend="underline">that</hi> passage<lb/>
                referred to the <hi rend="underline">High Priest</hi>! I was<lb/> satisfied and our
                engagement<lb/> went on, to the knowledge more or<lb/> less of nearly all the Jews
                in the</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">3</p>
            <p>city, for <persName>Mr. P.</persName> and myself regularly attended<lb/> synagogue
                during that period we<lb/> visited at <persName>Dr. Henry's</persName> certainly <hi
                    rend="underline">once</hi> a<lb/> week (many times more frequently) and he, and
                the<lb/> late <persName>Mrs. Henry</persName> used repeatedly ask what<lb/> we
                visited for? On the <date>15<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of Feb.<lb/> 1859</date>
                <persName>Mr. P.</persName> applied to the Board of the<lb/> Congregation “Sherith
                Israel” for permission<lb/> to marry—which was granted and,<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline"><persName>Dr. Henry</persName> had written and fitted out</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">our Casubba</hi> a thing he subsequently<lb/> told us he very
                seldom did before the<lb/> day it was wanted. So much for <persName>Dr<lb/>
                    Henry's</persName> refusal!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">On the <date>24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of Feb.</date> the day
                previous<lb/> to the one appointed for our marriage<lb/>
                <persName>Dr. Henry</persName> called at ½ 7 A. M. and after<lb/> some slight
                circumlocution asked me<lb/> if my former Husband had Brothers?<lb/>
                <sic>at</sic> first I could not recollect, I felt<lb/> confused and without knowing
                why<lb/> felt certain <persName>Dr. H</persName> had not come on<lb/> a friendly
                errand. I said I believed<lb/> there were two but I was not sure</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">4</p>
            <p>if there were more or not, he asked me<lb/> if I had had “Halitza”? I replied
                “Doctor<lb/> you know that is not done any more at<lb/> home” I cannot help it “he
                said” a<lb/> man named <persName>Ephraim</persName> says he was at school<lb/> with
                a Brother of your husband's 17 years<lb/> ago, a Trustee meeting has been
                held—the<lb/> Trustees leave it to me, and I cannot<lb/> marry you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You may imagine my feelings<lb/> Revd. Sir, I had been in
                    <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> nearly 10 years, had been a widow 7,<lb/>
                had shown a good example and<lb/> felt dreadfully aggrieved to be so served<lb/> at
                the last moment. <persName>Mr. P.</persName> said “never<lb/> mind we will go to a
                Magistrate”<lb/> I replied no—I am very angry<lb/> now, in an hour I shall be more
                com-<lb/>-posed, I will go round to <persName>Dr. Henry</persName><lb/> and ask him
                these questions, if he<lb/> answers me satisfactorily we will marry—<lb/>if not, we
                part. I will never see you<lb/> again—if you please you may</p>
            <div>
                <p>
                    <ref target="Occident_PDFs/Occ_20_1.pdf">The above text refers to Occident
                        Volume 20 No. 1 pages 15 through 19. Click here to view.</ref>
                </p>
            </div>
